Below is an example that's good

What is the definition of the derivative of \(f\) at \(a\)?
A function \(f\) is differentiable at \(a\) if the limit \[f'(a)=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}\] exists as a finite real number.

These should all be of that form

What does it mean for \(f\) to be continuous at \(a\)?
A function \(f\) is continuous at \(a\) if \[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=f(a).\] Equivalently: for every \(\varepsilon>0\), there exists \(\delta>0\) such that if \(|x-a|<\delta\), then \(|f(x)-f(a)|<\varepsilon\).

What is the \(\varepsilon\)-\(\delta\) definition of \(\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=L\)?
\[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=L\] means: for every \(\varepsilon>0\), there exists \(\delta>0\) such that if \(0<|x-a|<\delta\), then \(|f(x)-L|<\varepsilon\).

What is the definition of convergence of a sequence \((a_n)\) to \(L\)?
The sequence \((a_n)\) converges to \(L\) if for every \(\varepsilon>0\), there exists \(N\in\mathbb{N}\) such that for all \(n\ge N\), \[|a_n-L|<\varepsilon.\]

What is the definition of uniform continuity of \(f\) on a set \(A\)?
A function \(f:A\to\mathbb{R}\) is uniformly continuous on \(A\) if for every \(\varepsilon>0\), there exists \(\delta>0\) such that for all \(x,y\in A\), if \(|x-y|<\delta\), then \[|f(x)-f(y)|<\varepsilon.\] The key point is that \(\delta\) depends only on \(\varepsilon\), not on the point.

State the Intermediate Value Theorem (IVT).
If \(f\) is continuous on the closed interval \([a,b]\), and \(N\) is any number between \(f(a)\) and \(f(b)\), then there exists \(c\in[a,b]\) such that \[f(c)=N.\]

State the Extreme Value Theorem (EVT).
If \(f\) is continuous on the closed interval \([a,b]\), then \(f\) attains both an absolute maximum and an absolute minimum on \([a,b]\). That is, there exist \(x_{\min},x_{\max}\in[a,b]\) such that \[f(x_{\min})\le f(x)\le f(x_{\max})\quad\text{for all }x\in[a,b].\]

State Rolle's Theorem.
If \(f\) is continuous on \([a,b]\), differentiable on \((a,b)\), and \(f(a)=f(b)\), then there exists \(c\in(a,b)\) such that \[f'(c)=0.\]

State the Mean Value Theorem (MVT).
If \(f\) is continuous on \([a,b]\) and differentiable on \((a,b)\), then there exists \(c\in(a,b)\) such that \[f'(c)=\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}.\]

Why is Rolle's Theorem a special case of the Mean Value Theorem?
If \(f(a)=f(b)\), then the MVT conclusion becomes \[f'(c)=\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}=0,\] which is exactly Rolle's Theorem.

What is the geometric meaning of the Mean Value Theorem?
If \(f\) is continuous on \([a,b]\) and differentiable on \((a,b)\), then at some point \(c\in(a,b)\), the tangent line has the same slope as the secant line through \((a,f(a))\) and \((b,f(b))\).

What does differentiable at \(a\) imply about continuity at \(a\)?
If \(f\) is differentiable at \(a\), then \(f\) is continuous at \(a\). Differentiability is strictly stronger than continuity.

What is the definition of a Cauchy sequence?
A sequence \((a_n)\) is Cauchy if for every \(\varepsilon>0\), there exists \(N\in\mathbb{N}\) such that for all \(m,n\ge N\), \[|a_n-a_m|<\varepsilon.\]

What is the completeness property of \(\mathbb{R}\)?
Every Cauchy sequence of real numbers converges to a real number. Equivalently, every nonempty subset of \(\mathbb{R}\) that is bounded above has a least upper bound (supremum).

What is the identity for \(\sin A-\sin B\)?
\[\sin A-\sin B = 2\cos\left(\frac{A+B}{2}\right)\sin\left(\frac{A-B}{2}\right).\]

What must you check before applying Rolle's Theorem?
You must check all three hypotheses: \(f\) is continuous on \([a,b]\), \(f\) is differentiable on \((a,b)\), and \(f(a)=f(b)\).

What must you check before applying the Mean Value Theorem?
You must check both hypotheses: \(f\) is continuous on \([a,b]\) and \(f\) is differentiable on \((a,b)\).

If \(f'(x)=0\) for every \(x\in(a,b)\), what does the Mean Value Theorem imply about \(f\)?
\(f\) is constant on \((a,b)\). For any \(x<y\) in the interval, the MVT gives a \(c\in(x,y)\) with \[f'(c)=\frac{f(y)-f(x)}{y-x}=0,\] so \(f(y)=f(x)\).

If \(f'(x)>0\) for every \(x\in(a,b)\), what does the Mean Value Theorem imply?
\(f\) is strictly increasing on \((a,b)\). For \(x<y\), the MVT gives \[f(y)-f(x)=f'(c)(y-x)\] for some \(c\in(x,y)\). Since both factors on the right are positive, \(f(y)>f(x)\).

How does the Mean Value Theorem give the estimate \(|f(b)-f(a)|\le M|b-a|\)?
If \(|f'(x)|\le M\) on \((a,b)\), then by the MVT there is \(c\in(a,b)\) such that \[f(b)-f(a)=f'(c)(b-a).\] Taking absolute values gives \[|f(b)-f(a)|=|f'(c)||b-a|\le M|b-a|.\]

If \(f\) is differentiable on \((a,b)\) and continuous on \([a,b]\) with \(f(a)=f(b)\), what are you guaranteed to find?
By Rolle's Theorem, there exists \(c\in(a,b)\) such that \[f'(c)=0.\]

If \(f(0)=2\) and \(f(3)=11\), what slope does the Mean Value Theorem guarantee occurs somewhere in \((0,3)\)?
The secant slope is \[\frac{f(3)-f(0)}{3-0}=\frac{11-2}{3}=3.\] So the MVT guarantees some \(c\in(0,3)\) with \(f'(c)=3\).

How can you prove that a differentiable function is constant on an interval if it takes the same value at every pair of endpoints?
Use Rolle's Theorem on any subinterval \([x,y]\). Since \(f(x)=f(y)\), there exists \(c\in(x,y)\) with \(f'(c)=0\). More directly, if you know \(f'(x)=0\) everywhere, then MVT implies \(f(y)-f(x)=0\) for all \(x,y\), so \(f\) is constant.

If two differentiable functions \(f\) and \(g\) satisfy \(f'(x)=g'(x)\) on an interval, what can you conclude?
\(f-g\) has derivative \(0\) everywhere on the interval, so by the Mean Value Theorem \(f-g\) is constant. Therefore \[f(x)=g(x)+C\] for some constant \(C\).

Why does the function \(f(x)=|x|\) on \([-1,1]\) show that differentiability is necessary in Rolle's Theorem?
\(f\) is continuous on \([-1,1]\) and satisfies \(f(-1)=f(1)\), but it is not differentiable at \(0\). There is no \(c\in(-1,1)\) with \(f'(c)=0\), since \(f'(x)=-1\) for \(x<0\) and \(f'(x)=1\) for \(x>0\).

If \(f'(x)\le 0\) for all \(x\in(a,b)\), what does the Mean Value Theorem imply?
\(f\) is nonincreasing on \((a,b)\). For \(x<y\), the MVT gives \[f(y)-f(x)=f'(c)(y-x)\] for some \(c\in(x,y)\). Since \(f'(c)\le 0\) and \(y-x>0\), we get \(f(y)\le f(x)\).
